  "local_port": 48160,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What happened to Mt. Gox?",
  "response": "Mt. Gox, short for \"**Magic: The Gathering Online Exchange**,\" was one of the first and largest Bitcoin exchanges in the world. It was launched in 2010 by Jed McCaleb and later sold to Mark Karpel\u00e8s in 2011. At its peak, Mt. Gox handled over 70% of all Bitcoins traded globally. However, it became infamous for its catastrophic collapse in 2014 due to a combination of mismanagement, security vulnerabilities, and massive theft.\n\n### Key Events Leading to the Collapse:\n\n1. **Security Breaches and Hacks**:\n   - Mt. Gox suffered multiple hacking incidents over the years, with the most significant breach occurring between 2011 and 2014. Hackers exploited vulnerabilities in the exchange\u2019s systems to steal Bitcoin gradually.\n   - By February 2014, it was revealed that approximately **850,000 Bitcoins** (worth around $450 million at the time) had been stolen from the exchange\u2019s wallets. This included both customer funds and the company\u2019s reserves.\n\n2. **Mismanagement and Operational Issues**:\n   - Mt. Gox faced severe technical and operational problems, including delays in processing withdrawals, lack of proper accounting, and failure to implement robust security measures.\n   - The exchange\u2019s CEO, Mark Karpel\u00e8s, was accused of poor leadership and misusing customer funds, though he ultimately denied criminal intent.\n\n3. **Shutdown and Bankruptcy**:\n   - On **February 7, 2014**, Mt. Gox suspended all Bitcoin withdrawals, citing technical issues. This led to widespread panic and a sharp drop in Bitcoin\u2019s price.\n   - On **February 28, 2014**, Mt. Gox filed for bankruptcy protection in Japan, revealing that it had lost nearly 750,000 Bitcoins belonging to its users and 100,000 of its own Bitcoins.\n   - The total loss was valued at approximately **$473 million** at the time, making it one of the largest financial scandals in the cryptocurrency world.\n\n4. **Aftermath**:\n   - In the years following the collapse, a portion of the lost Bitcoins (around 200,000) was recovered. These funds were placed under the control of a court-appointed trustee to compensate affected creditors.\n   - The bankruptcy process dragged on for years, with creditors awaiting repayment. In 2021, a rehabilitation plan was approved, allowing creditors to receive compensation in Bitcoin or Bitcoin Cash, depending on their original claims.\n   - The collapse of Mt. Gox significantly damaged trust in cryptocurrency exchanges and highlighted the need for better regulation, security, and transparency in the industry.\n\n### Legacy:\nMt. Gox\u2019s collapse remains a cautionary tale in the cryptocurrency world. It underscored the risks of centralized exchanges and the importance of secure storage (e.g., cold wallets) for digital assets. It also contributed to the development of more robust regulatory frameworks and security practices in the crypto industry.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
